 {"id":"bd-39vt","title":"IOCP reactor: Windows native I/O completion ports","description":"# IOCP Reactor Implementation (Windows)

## Overview
Implements the Reactor trait using I/O Completion Ports (IOCP), the native
high-performance I/O mechanism on Windows.

## Background
IOCP is fundamentally different from epoll/kqueue:
- Completion-based, not readiness-based
- Operations are submitted, completions are received
- Uses overlapped I/O structures
- Highly scalable for server workloads

## Design Challenges

### Readiness vs Completion Model
IOCP is completion-based but our Reactor trait is readiness-based. Strategy:
1. Convert readiness interest to pending read/write operations
2. On poll(), receive completions and convert to readiness events
3. Maintain internal state to track which operations are pending

### AFD Polling (Advanced)
Windows provides AFD (Ancillary Function Driver) for socket readiness polling,
similar to epoll. This is what mio uses. More complex but closer to our model.

```rust
pub struct IocpReactor {
    /// IOCP handle
    iocp: HANDLE,
    /// Registered sockets with their state
    sockets: RwLock<HashMap<RawSocket, SocketState>>,
    /// AFD helper for readiness polling
    afd: AfdHelper,
}

struct SocketState {
    token: usize,
    interest: Interest,
    pending_ops: PendingOps,
}
```

### Reactor Implementation
```rust
impl Reactor for IocpReactor {
    fn register(&self, fd: RawFd, token: usize, interest: Interest) -> io::Result<()> {
        // Associate socket with IOCP
        let handle = fd as HANDLE;
        if unsafe {
            CreateIoCompletionPort(handle, self.iocp, token, 0)
        }.is_null() {
            return Err(io::Error::last_os_error());
        }

        // Register with AFD for polling
        self.afd.register(fd, interest)?;

        self.sockets.write().unwrap().insert(fd, SocketState {
            token,
            interest,
            pending_ops: PendingOps::default(),
        });

        Ok(())
    }

    fn poll(&self, events: &mut Events, timeout: Option<Duration>) -> io::Result<usize> {
        let timeout_ms = timeout.map_or(INFINITE, |d| d.as_millis() as u32);

        let mut entries = vec![unsafe { std::mem::zeroed() }; events.capacity];
        let mut count = 0u32;

        let result = unsafe {
            GetQueuedCompletionStatusEx(
                self.iocp,
                entries.as_mut_ptr(),
                entries.len() as u32,
                &mut count,
                timeout_ms,
                FALSE,
            )
        };

        if result == FALSE {
            let err = io::Error::last_os_error();
            if err.raw_os_error() == Some(WAIT_TIMEOUT as i32) {
                return Ok(0);
            }
            return Err(err);
        }

        // Convert completions to events
        for i in 0..count as usize {
            let entry = &entries[i];
            let token = entry.lpCompletionKey;
            // Determine readiness from completion type
            events.push(Event { token, ready: /* ... */ });
        }

        Ok(count as usize)
    }

    fn wake(&self) -> io::Result<()> {
        if unsafe {
            PostQueuedCompletionStatus(self.iocp, 0, WAKE_TOKEN, std::ptr::null_mut())
        } == FALSE {
            return Err(io::Error::last_os_error());
        }
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

